KDPI and EPTS

1. KDRI and KDPI

1.1 Introduction

In the field of kidney transplantation, evaluating the quality of donor kidneys is crucial due to the persistent shortage of available organs. Two important indices have been developed to assess donor quality: the Kidney Donor Risk Index (KDRI) and the Kidney Donor Profile Index (KDPI).

1.2 The Kidney Donor Risk Index (KDRI)

1.2.1 Definition and Purpose

The KDRI is a continuous metric that quantifies the relative risk of graft failure, which was defined as return to dialysis, retransplant, or death, after kidney transplantation from a deceased donor. It provides a way to compare donor kidneys based on clinical and demographic factors.

1.2.2 Origin and Reference

The KDRI model was first proposed by Rao etal.(2009) in the journal Transplantation\(^{1}\). It is based on a multivariable Cox proportional hazards model that estimated the hazard of graft loss or death after transplantation. Global model fit was calculated using discrimination (concordance = 0.6, also known as the C-statistic) and calibration (Integrated Brier score = 0.13).

1.2.3 Model Formula

The stratified Cox model underlying the KDRI is

\[ h(t \mid \mathbf Z, s) \,=\, h_{0,s}(t)\, \exp(\boldsymbol\beta^{\!\top}\mathbf Z), \]

where

  • \(\mathbf Z = (Z_1,\ldots,Z_p)\) is the covariate vector for the \(p=8\) donor factors listed in Section1.2.4;
  • \(s\) indexes the stratum determined by transplant centre, singleyear recipient age, and recipient diabetes status. (not straified by OPO)
  • \(h_{0,s}(t)\) is the baseline hazard in stratum\(s\).

Hence, the Kidney Donor Risk Index for donor\(i\) is

\[ \text{KDRI}_i\;=\;\frac{h(t\mid \mathbf Z_i)}{h(t\mid \mathbf Z_{\text{ref}})} \,=\, \exp\!\Bigl\{\boldsymbol\beta^{\!\top}(\mathbf Z_i-\mathbf Z_{\text{ref}})\Bigr\} \,=\,\prod_{j=1}^{p} \mathrm{HR}_j^{\,Z_{ij}-Z_{\text{ref},j}},\qquad \mathrm{HR}_j \equiv e^{\beta_j}. \]

1.2.4 Model Variables

Raoetal. initially included 10 donor factors. In the current OPTN operational model (approved October2024) this has been streamlined to 8 donor factors:

  1. Donor age(yrs)
  2. Donor height(cm)
  3. Donor weight(kg)
  4. History of hypertension(yes/no)
  5. History of diabetes(yes/no)
  6. Cause of death(cerebrovascular accidentvsother)
  7. Serum creatinine(mg/dL)
  8. Donation after cardiac death (DCD, yes/no)

Black race and hepatitisC virus (HCV) seropositivity were removed during the 2024 refit.

1.2.5 Model Dataset

The latest refit used graft outcomes from 50769 adult, firsttime, deceaseddonor kidneyalone transplants performed in the United States between 2018and2021 (followup through June2024).

1.2.6 Reference Donor Definition

The reference donor (KDRI=1.0) has:

  • Age40yr
  • Height170cm
  • Weight\(\ge\)80kg
  • No diabetes
  • No hypertension
  • Cause of death other than cerebrovascular accident
  • Terminal creatinine=1.0mg/dL
  • Braindeath donor (notdonation after cardiac death)

All other donors are compared against this reference profile.

1.2.10 Applicability

KDRI applies only to deceased donors. Livingdonor analogues such as the Living Kidney Donor Profile Index (LKDPI)\(^{5}\) are not used for allocation.

1.3 The Kidney Donor Profile Index (KDPI)

1.3.1 Definition

KDPI is defined as the percentile rank (0100%) of a donor kidneys Scaled KDRI against the U.S. donor pool from the previous calendar year.

1.3.2 Calculation

First calaulate the Scaled KDRI using the following formular.

\[ \mathrm{KDRI}_{\text{SCALED}} = \frac{\mathrm{KDRI}_{\text{RAO}}}{\text{scaling factor}} \]

The scaling factor is the median \(\mathrm{KDRI}_{\text{RAO}}\) value among all kidney donors recovered during the previous calendar year (e.g.scaling factor = 1.404 in 2024).

Let \(F_{\text{year}}\) be the empirical cumulative distribution function (CDF) of Scaled KDRI values for deceased donors in a given reference year. Then

\(\text{KDPI} = 100\% \times F_{\text{year}}(\mathrm{KDRI}_{\text{SCALED}}).\)

1.3.3 Annual Reference Distribution

  • The 2024 OPTN guide illustrates KDPI using 2022 donor data\(^{2}\).
  • The most recent public mapping file is based on 2023 donors\(^{3}\).

Hence KDPI reflects yeartoyear changes in donor risk.

1.3.4 Worked Example

A donor with KDRI=1.51 lies at the 90th percentile of the 2023 donor distribution : KDPI=90%.

1.3.5 Evaluation of KDPI (C-Index)

The predictive power of the KDPI is moderate of C-Index = 0.6.

2. EPTS: Estimated PostTransplant Survival Score

2.1 Definition and Purpose

The Estimated PostTransplant Survival (EPTS) score (0100%) estimates how long a candidate is expected to live after transplantation. Lower scores imply longer expected survival. Kidneys with KDPI\(\le\)20% are offered first to candidates with EPTS\(\le\)20%.

2.2 Origin

Developed by the Scientific Registry of Transplant Recipients (SRTR) for the OPTN Kidney Committee\(^{4}\).

2.3 Usage Conditions

  • Applies only to adult candidates (\(\ge\)18yr).
  • Priority rule: KDPI\(\le\)20% kidneys candidates with EPTS\(\le\)20%.

2.4 Raw EPTS Formula

\[ \begin{aligned} \text{Raw EPTS} =\ & 0.047 \times \max(\text{Age} - 25,\ 0) - 0.015 \times \text{Diabetes} \times \max(\text{Age} - 25,\ 0) \\ & + 0.398 \times \text{Prior Solid Organ Transplant} - 0.237 \times \text{Diabetes} \times \text{Prior Organ Transplant} \\ & + 0.315 \times \log(\text{Years on Dialysis} + 1) - 0.099 \times \text{Diabetes} \times \log(\text{Years on Dialysis} + 1) \\ & + 0.130 \times I(\text{Years on Dialysis} = 0) - 0.348 \times \text{Diabetes} \times I(\text{Years on Dialysis} = 0) + 1.262 \times \text{Diabetes} \end{aligned} \]

  • log() denotes the natural logarithm.

  • Indicator\(I(\cdot)\) equals1 if the condition is true, otherwise0.

  • Binary covariates Diabetes and PriorTx take value1 when present and0 otherwise.

The final EPTS score is the percentile of the raw score within the national adult waitlist on 31Dec2023 (updated annually).

2.5 Model Variables

The four predictors in the original Cox model were: age, diabetes, prior transplant history, and dialysis duration.

2.6 Model History

OPTN is exploring a Composite Allocation Score (CAS) that aggregates ten attributesKDPI/EPTS matching, waiting time, geography, HLA, etc.into a single 0100 scale.

2.7 Interpretation

  • EPTS=0%: longest expected survival
  • EPTS=100%: shortest expected survival
  • EPTS\(\le\)20% triggers priority for KDPI\(\le\)20% kidneys.
